pr_review_comment_body:
Instead of this, I would so something like:

var projectName = defaultProjectName ? defaultProjectName : thDefaultRepo;

That removes the need for a bunch of if/else clauses.

I think both `initVisualization` and `updateVisType` should be invoked here. Maybe this way:

```javascript
var visType = $(this).val();
changeState('visType', visType);
initVisualisation(visType);
updateVisType(visType);
```

@nicoe That's a good point, thanks for pointing that out.

I've been in contact with the maintainer of https://github.com/bryanjos/geo, which is a similar library for Elixir. We both ran into the same use case and I'd like to come with a semi-standard approach.

In any case, you're right; if the SRID is an int it might as well just be an int in the output (rather than a string).

If you make the store the first argument you can create this anonymous function earlier and bind it:

const boundHandleGistError = handleGistError.bind(null, store)

Then pass boundHandleGistError to the catch.

Would it be worth collapsing these if statements into one?
```
if ( (aAddress->length == RAIL_IEEE802154_LongAddress &&
      findSrcMatchExtEntry(aAddress->longAddress) >= 0 ) ||
     (aAddress->length != RAIL_IEEE802154_LongAddress &&
      findSrcMatchShortEntry(aAddress->shortAddress) >= 0) )
{
    RAIL_IEEE802154_SetFramePending();
}
```

nit:
```
else:
    if:
```

should just be `elif:`.
